+# v0.8 Mobile Share Import
+
+Date: 2026-06-09
+Phase: mobile share/import preview
+Status: PASS for mobile share/import preview
+
+## Goal
+
+Import files shared from a phone, sync folder, or ZIP into Pala Memory Core so mobile ChatGPT notes, PDFs, screenshots, and text exports can be preserved locally.
+
+## Added Behavior
+
+| Area | Change |
+|---|---|
+| CLI | Added `python pala.py import mobile-share <path>` |
+| Inputs | File, folder, or ZIP |
+| Text inputs | `.json`, `.html`, `.md`, `.txt` become memory records |
+| Attachments | PDF, images, and Office files are copied as attachments |
+| Source | Stores record source as `mobile` |
+| Tags | Adds `mobile-share` plus optional user tags |
+
+## Command
+
+```powershell
+python .\pala.py import mobile-share .\data\inbox\mobile-share-smoke --project trugurpala/pala-memory-core --tag smoke-test
+```
+
+## Expected Result
+
+```text
+saved <record-id>
+data\records\<date>\<record-id>.md
+imported <n> text record(s) and <m> attachment file(s) from <path>
+```
+
+## Smoke Test
+
+Created a sample shared folder with one Markdown note and one PDF-like attachment, then imported it:
+
+```powershell
+python .\pala.py import mobile-share .\data\inbox\mobile-share-smoke --project trugurpala/pala-memory-core --tag smoke-test --max-records 5 --max-chars 2000
+python .\pala.py brief today
+python .\pala.py dashboard export
+```
+
+Observed output:
+
+```text
+saved 20260609T133804Z-mobile-share-chatgpt-mobile-note
+data\records\2026-06-09\20260609T133804Z-mobile-share-chatgpt-mobile-note.md
+saved 20260609T133804Z-mobile-share-attachments
+data\records\2026-06-09\20260609T133804Z-mobile-share-attachments.md
+imported 1 text record(s) and 1 attachment file(s) from C:\Users\Pala-Home-1\Desktop\Codex\pala-memory-core\data\inbox\mobile-share-smoke
+brief saved data\reports\2026-06-09-brief.md
+dashboard data saved dashboard\records.json
+```
+
+## Release Posture
+
+This is a share/import preview. It does not monitor phones in the background; the reliable first path is share/copy to a folder, then import.
